observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

a. instruct the Municipal Social Welfare Development Officer (MSWDO) and BAC to provide a written explanation on the delayed implementation of SFP and ensure timely implementation thereof for the benefit of the intended beneficiaries;


b. instruct the BHWs concerned to submit a written explanation on the discrepancies between the submitted DTRs and logbooks of BHWs; provide valid proofs that they physically report for work and have provided direct health/support care as well as valid reasons for failure to sign in the logbook of the Barangay;

c. Punong Barangays, being the head of the health facility, to ensure that DTRs were based on the logbook to avoid discrepancies in the amounts to be claimed;


d. require concerned employees to refund the amount of ₱5,112.50 representing excess claims; and


e. submit a legal basis in the grant of OCA to National Government personnel in order to validate the legality and validity of payment of OCA.

We recommended that Management:

a. establish the GAD Database and ensure complete and timely implementation of GAD PPAs so that, desired results and benefits for the intended recipients/beneficiaries are fully achieved;

b. formulate the LGU GAD Code in support of the LGU’s efforts in promoting, protecting and fulfilling women’s human rights, women’s economic empowerment and gender-responsive governance towards the attainment of gender equality and women’s empowerment;

c. issue an E.O. reorganizing/reconstituting the GFPS of the LGU as required by PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, as amended by JMC No. 2016-01; and


d. ensure that GAD AR is supported with the requirements mentioned under Section 5.C.8.5 of the PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:

a. HRMO to

(i) submit the CY 2022 DTRs and Accomplishment Reports of Casuals and JO personnel for audit;


(ii) determine the whereabouts and submit reason or justification for the non-appearance of 35 subject personnel during the headcount. Likewise, implement stricter control mechanisms in the monitoring of the attendance of Casuals and JO personnel to ensure that they remain productive in their respective area of assignments within the designated time schedule of duty;


(iii) revisit and evaluate the responsibilities and job descriptions of employees to avoid possible duplication of work and ensure that they are assigned to offices that are in dire need of their services;


(iv) prepare a complete Organizational Structure and Staffing Pattern of the LGU so that the necessity and propriety of hiring the JO personnel are justified;


(v) stop the practice of hiring local elective officials in any capacity to any public office or position; and payment of overtime to JO personnel in order to prevent the issuance of a Notice of Disallowance (ND); and


b. HRMO, Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to ensure that the claims for services of Casuals and JO personnel are supported with complete and appropriate documentation.

3.41	We recommended that Management:
require the Municipal Assessor to expedite the titling of recorded parcels of land in compliance with Section 148 of COA Circular No. 92-386 and Section 39 of P.D. 1445 to establish ownership thereof and to fully protect the interest of the Municipality;
enjoin the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with Municipal Assessor to exert further efforts in the retrieval of documents required to establish ownership and cost valuation of the unrecorded land to facilitate its recording in the books at acquisition cost, or fair value, if acquired through the non-exchange transaction;
require the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjusting journal entries to (a) reclassify the completed projects including the corresponding depreciation thereof; (b) record the cost of first and final payment for the project Improvement of Evacuation Center with a net effect of ₱655,058.54; and (c) locate pertinent records to trace the details of the CIP accounts, reclassify the completed projects to appropriate asset accounts and provide the corresponding depreciation; and
instruct the MENRO to continuously follow up with EMB R-3 for the necessary documents that would show the valuation of the donated PPE for proper recognition in the books of the Municipality.

9.15	We recommended that Management:
instruct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to ensure that the timeframe for each procurement stage/activity has been strictly followed;
advise the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the BAC for the completion and submission of the noted documentary deficiencies and ensure that only disbursement vouchers with complete documentation are processed and presented for payment;
instruct the Inspectorate Team and the Municipal Engineer to submit a written explanation regarding the issuance of Certificate of Completion and Acceptance on the project Completion of Slaughterhouse at Barangay Binabalian prior to its completion; and
determine the actual completion date of the afore-cited project in order to compute the amount of corresponding liquidated damages and demand payment thereof from the contractor.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) instruct the:

a.	Municipal Accountant to 

(i) maintain SLC for each commodity/stock; 



(ii) record all procurement of inventory supplies in the books of accounts using the Perpetual Inventory System; 

(iii) draw the necessary journal entries to recognize the amount of Drugs and Medicines and Medical, Dental and Laboratory Inventory as at year-end amounting to ₱197,875.00 and ₱33,274.00, respectively; and

(iv) be more vigilant to ensure that issued supplies and materials were recorded to appropriate expense accounts; and



b.	Supply Officer to 

(i) maintain stock cards for each item of inventory; 

(ii) regularly reconcile the stock cards with the SLCs of the Accounting Office; 

(iii) report the issuances of supplies thru the SSMI which shall be the basis of the Municipal Accountant in recording to appropriate Expenses accounts; and 

(iv) conduct physical count of stocks of all supplies and materials and submit relative reports to the Office of the Auditor and other offices concerned on a semi-annual basis.

We recommended that the LCE instruct the Municipal Accountant to draw necessary Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) to:

a.	derecognize in the books the recorded CIP – Infrastructure Assets account by debiting the Government Equity account for ₱1,786,454.32 and crediting PPE account for the same amount; 

b.	adjust/correct erroneous recording of PPE accounts totaling ₱2,487,290.53;



c.	provide depreciation for completed projects totaling ₱80,710.39; and




d.	revert the entry on depreciation prior to the completion of projects Rehabilitation of Day Care Center at Barangay Libertador and Taposo and the corresponding Accumulated Depreciation amounting to ₱59,010.30.

We recommended that the LCE:

a.	coordinate with the Local Development Council and undertake a thorough evaluation of the programs, projects and activities to be funded under the 20% Development Fund and stop from charging expenditures which do not partake the nature of investment and capital expenditures;

b.	practice the issuance of Suspension Order for suspended projects either wholly or partly for a certain period of time in accordance Annex D Item No. 2.1 of the revised IRR of RA 9184 otherwise, impose liquidated damages to the contractor; 

c.	instruct the Municipal Community Affairs Assistant to explain in writing how did the 102 farmers received the full amount of ₱19,500.00 or a total of ₱1,989,000.00 even though the amount paid to Oriental Seed Growers Agriculture Cooperative was only ₱1,909,440.00; and

d.	instruct the Municipal Accountant to verify all supporting documents as to completeness and see to it that the same are attached to the disbursement vouchers before payments are made to establish the legality and proper accountability over financial transactions.

2.6	We recommended that the LCE instruct the Municipal Accountant to draw necessary Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) to:
derecognize in the books the recorded CIP – Infrastructure Assets account by debiting the Government Equity account for ₱1,786,454.32 and crediting PPE account for the same amount;
adjust/correct erroneous recording of PPE accounts totaling ₱2,487,290.53;
provide depreciation for completed projects totaling ₱80,710.39; and
revert the entry on depreciation prior to the completion of projects Rehabilitation of Day Care Center at Barangay Libertador and Taposo and the corresponding Accumulated Depreciation amounting to ₱59,010.30.

3.10	We recommended that the LCE:
coordinate with the Local Development Council and undertake a thorough evaluation of the programs, projects and activities to be funded under the 20% Development Fund and stop from charging expenditures which do not partake the nature of investment and capital expenditures;
practice the issuance of Suspension Order for suspended projects either wholly or partly for a certain period of time in accordance Annex D Item No. 2.1 of the revised IRR of RA 9184 otherwise, impose liquidated damages to the contractor;
instruct the Municipal Community Affairs Assistant to explain in writing how did the 102 farmers received the full amount of ₱19,500.00 or a total of ₱1,989,000.00 even though the amount paid to Oriental Seed Growers Agriculture Cooperative was only ₱1,909,440.00; and
instruct the Municipal Accountant to verify all supporting documents as to completeness and see to it that the same are attached to the disbursement vouchers before payments are made to establish the legality and proper accountability over financial transactions.

4.10	We recommended that the LCE to:
direct the LDRRM Officer to strive for the timely and full implementation of LDRRM-related PPAs to achieved the goals and objective of the fund and the desired benefits;
instruct the Municipal Accountant and Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to (i) submit the aforementioned required documents immediately to the Office of the Auditor for proper/further evaluation of the transactions pursuant to Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445 and (ii) comply with the required reportorial requirements of GPPB Circular 2020-001 for information purposes and instruct the MDRRM Officer and Municipal Accountant to ensure timely preparation of the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF on or before the 15th day after the end of each month and submit to the Office of the Auditor within the aforesaid reglementary period;
require (i) the Property Officer to diligently prepare/maintain inventory records such as Stock Cards (SCs) and Property Cards (PCs), Monthly Report of Supplies and Materials Issued, RIS and Inventory List of all procured items and coordinate with the Accounting Office for the periodic reconciliation of both inventory records; and (ii) provide storage/stockroom located in accessible, safe and secured areas that will accommodate all supplies, medicines, materials, equipment and relief goods of the MDRRMO to ensure that relief goods are properly monitored, stored, safeguarded, avoid possible damage, spoilage, loss and pilferage; and
instruct the Municipal Accountant to draw a Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) to reflect the amount of accumulated depreciation of Flood Control System.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive undertake the following courses of action:

(a) cause the execution and submission of a MOA for all fund transfers which shall define the specific guidelines and procedures in the implementation of the individual projects, including the responsibilities of the LGU, thereby ensuring timely accomplishment thereof for the benefit of the intended beneficiaries; 

(b) direct the BAC and Technical Working Group (TWG) to fully scrutinize all eligibility documents submitted by the supplier in order to arrive at an accurate/appropriate decision and submit an explanation why KAE Construction and Supply was declared as the Single or Lowest Calculated and Responsive Bidder knowing that the eligibility requirements presented for evaluation were not appropriate and relevant;

(c) see to it that a Supplemental/Bid Bulletin is issued by the BAC/TWG at least seven calendar days before the deadline for the submission and receipt of bids whenever the Municipality, as the procuring entity, deems it necessary to clarify or modify any provisions of the Bidding Documents to ensure transparency in the procurement process; and

(d) instruct the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the BAC for the completion and submission of the documentary deficiencies noted and ensure that disbursement claims are supported with complete documentation before payments are made.

We recommended that management:

(a) undertake proper information dissemination like conduct of seminars, production of posters/tarpaulins on the harmful effects to public health of the smoke from burned solid wastes; 

(b) 	encourage the active participation of constituents, particularly the households, institutions, market vendors and commercial/business establishments in the proper waste disposal from source and seek the help of private companies/ organizations and schools in the conduct of a more aggressive and intensive information campaign on the proper segregation of wastes; 

(c) 	ensure that waste collectors and segregators are equipped with personal protective equipment to free them from the hazards of handling solid wastes; and

(d) 	coordinate with the barangay officials for the establishment and operation of Materials Recovery Facility (MRF) within their respective barangays pursuant to Section 32 of R.A. No. 9003.

4.23	We recommended that the Local Chief Executive undertake the following courses of action:
(a) cause the execution and submission of a MOA for all fund transfers which shall define the specific guidelines and procedures in the implementation of the individual projects, including the responsibilities of the LGU, thereby ensuring timely accomplishment thereof for the benefit of the intended beneficiaries;
(b) direct the BAC and Technical Working Group (TWG) to fully scrutinize all eligibility documents submitted by the supplier in order to arrive at an accurate/appropriate decision and submit an explanation why KAE Construction and Supply was declared as the Single or Lowest Calculated and Responsive Bidder knowing that the eligibility requirements presented for evaluation were not appropriate and relevant;
(c)  see to it that a Supplemental/Bid Bulletin is issued by the BAC/TWG at least seven calendar days before the deadline for the submission and receipt of bids whenever the Municipality, as the procuring entity, deems it necessary to clarify or modify any provisions of the Bidding Documents to ensure transparency in the procurement process; and
(d) instruct the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the BAC for the completion and submission of the documentary deficiencies noted and ensure that disbursement claims are supported with complete documentation before payments are made.

7.22	We recommended that management undertake the following courses of action:
conduct proper information dissemination like giving of seminars, and production of posters/tarpaulins on the harmful effects to public health of the smoke from burned solid wastes;
encourage the active participation of constituents, particularly the households, institutions, market vendors and commercial/business establishments in the proper waste disposal from source and seek the help of private companies/organizations and schools in the conduct of a more aggressive and intensive information campaign on the proper segregation of wastes;
ensure that waste collectors and segregators are equipped with personal protective equipment to free them from the hazards of handling solid wastes; and
coordinate with the barangay officials for the establishment and operation of Materials Recovery Facility (MRF) within their respective barangays pursuant to Section 32 of R.A. No. 9003.
7.23	During the exit conference, the designated MENRO commented that reminders, commendations, and letters have been continuously sent to all Punong Barangays for the purpose of promoting proper coordination, monitoring and implementation of environment plans in their respective areas of responsibility. Moreover, the MENRO has been continually working for the institutionalization of the Municipal Environmental and Natural Resources Office and the employment of sufficient manpower to handle the mandated functions of the Office. The Official also disclosed their commitment to conduct a meeting with the SWMB for the passing of an ordinance that will enforce the monitoring and apprehension of violators with the imposition of appropriate sanctions, such as penalty or rendition of service, as the case may be.

We recommended and management agreed to instruct: 

(a) the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator and the Municipal Engineer to (i) prepare and submit an Annual Procurement Plan for all development projects for consolidation by the BAC;(ii) plan and schedule properly activities relating to the projects to be undertaken by administration by indicating in the Program of Works (POW) the contract time/duration; (iii) ensure that the Municipality is technically capable to handle the projects “By Administration” by taking an inventory of existing skills before the actual project implementation; and (iv) include all projects/programs/
activities, regardless of fund source to the Quarterly Report submitted to this Office to promote transparency and accountability; 

(b) instruct the BAC and BAC Secretariat to submit the required documents to the Audit Team as enumerated in Appendix O, Part IV of this report; 


(c) instruct the Municipal Accountant to carefully scrutinize and review all documents attached to any disbursement voucher and make sure that the same were complete prior to certifying the completeness of supporting documents; otherwise the Audit Team will be forced to issue Notice of Disallowance; and 

(d) conduct monitoring of implemented projects to ensure attainment of desired socio-economic and environmental outcomes through (i) re-orientation of the barangay officials on the use and sole purpose of the Eco-Trikes; and (ii) train the dump truck driver on the high tech features of the new Dump truck to maximize its utilization for garbage collection.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator and the Municipal Engineer to properly plan and schedule activities relating to the development projects based on detailed engineering to cope with the timetable and commitment for the year; 

ensure that the Municipality is technically capable to handle the projects “By Administration” by taking an inventory of existing skills before the actual project implementation; and 

include all projects/programs/activities, regardless of fund source to the Quarterly Report submitted to this Office to promote transparency and accountability. In this manner, projects targetted for completion would be finished and reported on time for the benefit of the intended end-users/beneficiaries.

We recommended and management agreed to:

carefully plan the projects, programs and activities that may be included in the Local Disaster Risk Reduction Management Plan to see to it that only those items that are sanctioned and authorized by R.A. No. 10121 and NDRRMC –DBM –DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013 – 1 dated March 25, 2013 are included therein to prevent illegal and irregular disbursement of public funds;
cause the immediate opening of an account for the LDRRMF with the Landbank of the Philippines, Iba, Zambales pursuant to SB Resolution No. 55 dated November 13, 2017; 
and (c) strictly abide by the prescribed procedures for projects undertaken “ By Administration”.

We recommended that management instruct the Municipal Treasurer and the Market Administrator to:

strictly enforce the provisions of the Revenue Code;
consistently implement the issuance and approval of Application for Lease and Contract of Lease to all stallholders;
maintain a complete and updated registry book containing vital information about the stallholders; i.e. names and addresses, numbers, and description of stalls occupied, location, date and time of receipt of application, and contract period;

consider the revision of the policies concerning the rates to be imposed and define the front corner and inside corner stalls for proper collection of the fees dues;

impose additional rental fees for extension of stall spaces; and
sustain the policy on the grant of 20% discount to eligible stallholders to encourage prompt payments. Strict implementation of the provisions of the Code would benefit the Municipality in terms of increased collections of rental fees from market stalls which could be utilized to finance the improvement of market operations and other needs of the Municipality.

We recommended that management:

constantly follow – up its application for an ECC from the DENR to enable the MSWMB to fully and officially discharge its duties;
provide and require separate container for each type of waste from all sources and make sure that the same are properly marked or identified as "compostable", "non-recyclable", "recyclable" or "special waste", or any other classification to facilitate the sorting process and subsequent processing in the MRF;

revisit its Annual Budget for CY 2017 to determine the possibility of purchasing (i) a set of protective equipment for use of its collecting crews to avoid direct contact with hazardous wastes and (ii) one-unit garbage truck with complete specifications and compliant with the requirements of the Ecological Management Act of 2000; and
request the Sangguniang Bayan to legislate appropriate Ordinances in aid of the Act and in the enforcement of its provisions, particularly on the prohibitions against open burning of solid wastes.

We recommended that management:

make representation from ZAMECO I for the delivery of the transformer and facilitate the immediate installation thereof;



commence the operation of the New Public Market as soon as the needed facilities are acquired;
post invitation on conspicuous places informing interested individuals of the commencement of operation of the New Public Market and encouraging them to lease stalls thereof; and
take actions to attract consumers to visit and buy goods offered in the market.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the ICO-Municipal Accounting Office to:
 o prepare the Journal Entry Voucher for the transfer of unexpended balance of LDRRMF in the amount of P7,294,850.68  and reclassification of P81,903.60 from Other Payables to Trust Liabilities-DRRMF account;
 henceforth, maintain subsidiary ledgers for the transfer of unexpended balance by year of transfer and disclose the amount and details of the unexpended balance of LDRRMF in the Notes to Financial Statements;
» Municipal Budget Officer to obligate the continuing appropriation of P3,437,650.24 and request for a Sangguniang Barangay Resolution for the provision of budget in the GF for the remaining P3,857,200.44 to facilitate the transfer of fund; and
» Municipal Treasurer to effect the transfer of P7,294,850.68 form GF to STF once the obligation is approved.

We recommended that management direct the BAC to:

(a) refrain from awarding the succeeding procurement transactions to ineligible bidders, otherwise, the audit team will issue the necessary notice of disallowance to that effect;



(b) invite in writing, representatives from the Commission on Audit and from a duly recognized private group in a sector or discipline relevant to the procurement at hand, and from a non – government organization to enhance the transparency of the procurement process;



(c) ensure the widest dissemination of procurement – related notices; and



(d) ensure that all documents submitted by the bidders are valid and effective during the procurement period.



We also recommended that management instruct the Municipal Accountant to check that all supporting documents are complete and attached to the disbursement vouchers before payments are made.

We recommended that the management:
instruct the BAC to exert more effort in evaluating bid proposals and the qualifications of prospective bidders; be more cautious in declaring the lowest calculated and responsive bidder; and exercise more prudence in recommending award of contracts;
direct the BAC to submit to the Audit Team the following: (i) proof that a second bidding was conducted on the purchase of sixteen (16) units hand – held radio and DRRM equipment, and the declaring of a second failure of public bidding which thereafter occurred, prior to resorting to the alternative mode of procurement; (ii) the set of fully accomplished RFQs of participant suppliers/ dealers; and (iii) the documents relative to the Extension/Expansion of Existing Communal Irrigation System, and Supply and Delivery of Medical, Dental, Laboratory and Office Equipment; otherwise, we shall be constrained to issue the corresponding Notice of Suspension (NS);
We recommended that the management:
instruct the Focal Persons to submit copies of the MOAs executed between the Municipal Government of Candelaria, Zambales and the source government agencies, if any, and Project Proposals, if any, relative to all its BuB projects; and
refrain from authorizing payment of claims of suppliers/ contractors except when all pertinent supporting documents are attached thereto and the appropriate certifications by the concerned municipal officials/ employees are made.

We recommended that management instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

refrain from granting additional cash advances unless previous cash advances were already liquidated;

require the concerned personnel to liquidate their cash advances as soon as the purpose thereof had been accomplished; 

refrain from granting special cash advances to officials other than the designated special disbursing officers; 


ensure that cash advances are settled and reported on within the prescribed period of liquidation. Failure of the AO to liquidate his cash advance within the prescribed period shall constitute a valid cause for the withholding of his salary; and

 ensure that all cash advances are liquidated at the end of the year.


Further, adhere strictly to the provisions of COA Circular No. 97 – 002 and ensure continuous compliance thereon.
